{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657138","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657138"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:23:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:23:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19103"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19103","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19103"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11837"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81546"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11837"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19103"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66896"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5581"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27791"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27874"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27875"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81546"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for investigation of chronic headaches. She has a medical history of depression and surgical repair of an intracranial aneurysm 20 years ago. Two years previously she had a laparoscopic cholecystectomy. She has an intrauterine device in position. She takes sertraline and has multiple tattoos on her arms. She works as a welder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She has several visible tattoos on both arms and a surgical scar on her scalp.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer general practitioner is considering what type of imaging would be most appropriate and knows that a magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) scan would provide the best definition of her brain. However, there are limitations to MRI.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is an absolute contraindication to this form of imaging?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dental amalgam fillings","Copper intrauterine device","Metal sutures from recent surgery","Ferromagnetic intracranial aneurysm clip","Large arm tattoo"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESafety screening before MRI is crucial to prevent potentially fatal complications. Understanding absolute versus relative contraindications is essential for patient safety.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFerromagnetic intracranial aneurysm clips\u003C/strong\u003E are an absolute contraindication to MRI. The powerful magnetic field can cause movement of the clip, potentially leading to catastrophic intracranial haemorrhage. While modern aneurysm clips are typically MRI-compatible, older clips (pre-1995) may be ferromagnetic. Documentation of clip type must be verified before proceeding with MRI.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELarge arm tattoos\u003C/strong\u003E are a relative contraindication. Some tattoo inks contain metallic particles that can heat up during MRI, potentially causing local burning or irritation. However, with appropriate screening and patient monitoring, MRI can usually proceed safely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetal sutures\u003C/strong\u003E from recent surgery are a relative contraindication. While they may cause local image artifacts and minor tissue heating, they do not pose a significant safety risk. In this case, it is likely that the patient has some metallic clips at the site of her cholecystectomy. Any scan of this part of the body may be delayed until healing has occurred to minimise discomfort.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECopper intrauterine device\u003C/strong\u003E is a relative contraindication. Modern IUDs are typically MRI-compatible and may only cause local image artifacts. The device should be checked after an MRI scan to ensure it has not moved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDental amalgam fillings\u003C/strong\u003E are a relative contraindication. While they may cause local image artefacts, they are stable in magnetic fields and do not pose a safety risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther absolute contraindications include certain cardiac pacemakers, cochlear implants, and other ferromagnetic implanted devices. The key principle is that any ferromagnetic object near vital structures poses an unacceptable risk during MRI.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ferromagnetic intracranial aneurysm clips are an absolute contraindication to MRI due to risk of clip movement and fatal haemorrhage.","Relative contraindications to MRI can be managed with appropriate precautions and risk assessment.","Recent surgery, tattoos, and implanted devices require careful screening but are not absolute contraindications to MRI."],"references":["RACGP, Clinical guidance for MRI referral, 2013, https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/mri-referral/use-of-mri/contraindications-and-safety"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66896"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19103"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66896","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66896"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-26T10:50:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-26T10:52:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id"